    question:
      'How does the writer use language to create a sense of tension in the extract below?\n\nYou should comment on:\n- what is said\n- how it is said\n\nYou must refer to the text to support your comments.\n\n"The corridor stretched ahead of him, longer than he remembered, the ceiling lower, the walls closer. Each door he passed was shut. He tried one — locked. Another — locked. The third gave way with a sound that seemed too loud for the silence around it. Inside, the room was empty except for a single chair facing the window. The curtains had been drawn back, and through the glass he could see the garden below, motionless in the fading light. Nothing moved. Nothing at all. And yet he had the unmistakable feeling that he had arrived too late."',
    modelAnswer:
      'The writer creates a mounting sense of tension through a combination of spatial distortion, repetition, and psychological unease.\n\nThe opening sentence immediately establishes disorientation. The corridor is "longer than he remembered," suggesting that the familiar has become strange — a technique that unsettles the reader by implying the environment itself has shifted. The tricolon "longer than he remembered, the ceiling lower, the walls closer" uses a pattern of compression, with each clause shorter than the last, mirroring the physical narrowing of the space. This claustrophobic imagery creates a visceral sense of entrapment.\n\nRepetition is used to build frustration and dread. The parallel structure "He tried one — locked. Another — locked" mimics the character\'s repeated, futile attempts. The em dashes create abrupt, staccato pauses that interrupt the narrative flow, reflecting the sudden dead ends the character encounters. The brevity of these sentences contrasts sharply with the longer opening, accelerating the pace and heightening urgency.\n\nWhen the third door opens, the sound "seemed too loud for the silence around it" draws attention to the oppressive quiet. The writer uses the silence not as an absence of threat but as a container for it — the silence is a presence, something with weight and dimensions. This is reinforced by the description of the garden as "motionless in the fading light," where the adjective "fading" introduces temporal anxiety: time is running out.\n\nThe repetition of "Nothing moved. Nothing at all" uses anaphora and a short, emphatic fragment to create a pause that feels loaded with significance. The reader expects something to move; the insistence that nothing does creates suspense through denial of expectation.\n\nThe final sentence delivers the emotional climax: "the unmistakable feeling that he had arrived too late." The adjective "unmistakable" is crucial — it transforms a vague anxiety into a certainty, yet the writer never reveals what the character is too late for. This withholding of information is the most effective tension-building device in the extract. The reader is left with dread but no resolution, which sustains the tension beyond the passage itself.\n\nThe writer also employs a shift from external to internal perspective. The passage begins with physical description — corridors, doors, rooms — but ends with a psychological state. This movement inward mirrors the character\'s increasing isolation and suggests that the true source of tension is not the environment but the character\'s own apprehension.',
    markScheme:
      "AO2: Explain, comment on and analyse how writers use language and structure to achieve effects, using relevant subject terminology. Band 4 (8-10): Detailed, perceptive analysis of language with apt use of terminology and well-chosen examples. Band 3 (5-7): Clear, relevant analysis with some appropriate terminology. Band 2 (3-4): Some understanding of language features with limited terminology. Band 1 (1-2): Basic awareness with little or no terminology.",
