    questionNumber: "B2",
    difficulty: 3,
    marks: 40,
    timeMinutes: 45,
    question:
      'Write a narrative with the title "The Unexpected Visitor."\n\nYou could write about your own experience or create an imagined narrative. Focus on engaging the reader through careful control of pace, character, and atmosphere.\n\n(24 marks for communication and organisation, 16 marks for vocabulary, sentence structure, spelling, and punctuation)',
    modelAnswer:
      'The knock came at ten past eleven on a Thursday night, which is not a time when anyone knocks with good news.\n\nI had been reading — or rather, I had been holding a book and staring at the same paragraph for twenty minutes, the way you do when sleep is close but has not yet committed to arriving. The house was quiet. The heating had clicked off an hour ago, and the walls were beginning to make those small, private sounds that houses make when they think nobody is listening.\n\nThe knock came again. Three times, evenly spaced, neither urgent nor tentative. It was the knock of someone who expected to be answered.\n\nI went to the door and opened it without checking the peephole, which is the kind of decision that seems brave in the moment and stupid immediately afterwards.\n\nShe was standing on the step with a suitcase. Not a modern suitcase with wheels and an extendable handle, but an old leather one, the kind you see in films set during the war. It was battered and stickered and looked as though it had been carried a very long way by someone who had not enjoyed the journey.\n\n"I think you might be expecting me," she said.\n\nI was not expecting her. I had never seen her before. She was perhaps sixty, with grey hair cut short and practical, and she wore a coat that was too thin for November. Her eyes were the colour of strong tea, and they looked at me with an expression I could not immediately read — something between apology and recognition.\n\n"I\'m sorry," I said. "I think you have the wrong house."\n\n"Number thirty-seven," she said. It was not a question.\n\n"Yes, but —"\n\n"Then I have the right house." She smiled, and the smile changed her face entirely, the way sunlight changes a room. "May I come in? I\'ve come rather a long way, and I\'d prefer to explain sitting down."\n\nAgainst every instinct I possess, I stepped aside.\n\nShe walked into the hallway and stood for a moment, looking around with the careful attention of someone who is comparing what they see with what they remember. She touched the banister, briefly, the way you might touch something you had been thinking about for a long time.\n\n"The wallpaper is different," she said.\n\n"I\'m sorry?"\n\n"It used to be green. With small flowers. Cornflowers, I think." She paused. "But that would have been 1972."\n\nSomething shifted in my understanding. Not a revelation — more like the moment when you turn a kaleidoscope and the same pieces of glass rearrange themselves into a new pattern.\n\n"You lived here," I said.\n\n"I grew up here." She set the suitcase down in the hall. "I left when I was seventeen. I always meant to come back, and I never did, and now I am sixty-three and I have learned that the things you always mean to do are the things you must do immediately or not at all."\n\nI made tea. It is the only response the English have to the inexplicable, and it has served us well for centuries. She sat at my kitchen table and held the mug with both hands, and she told me about the house as it had been: the garden with the plum tree that produced fruit so sour nobody could eat it, the bedroom window that rattled in the wind, the crack in the bathroom ceiling that her father had promised to fix every Sunday for eleven years.\n\nI listened. The house listened too, or seemed to — the walls leaning in, the silence deepening into something that felt less like absence and more like attention.\n\nShe stayed for an hour. She did not ask to see the upstairs rooms, and I did not offer. Some things are better remembered than revisited. When she left, she shook my hand at the door and thanked me with a formality that made me want to cry, though I could not have explained why.\n\n"I hope the house is good to you," she said.\n\nI watched her walk down the path, her suitcase catching the light from the street lamp. At the gate, she turned and looked back — not at me, but at the house itself, taking it in the way you take a last look at a person you love before a long separation.\n\nThen she was gone, and the night closed around the space where she had been, and I went inside and locked the door and stood in the hallway for a long time, listening to the house breathe.',
