      'Using the text below, identify and summarise the key points the writer makes about life in Victorian factories.\n\nYou should use your own words as far as possible.\n\n"The factory bell sounded at half past five each morning, and those who did not arrive by six were locked out and lost a full day\'s wages. The rooms were kept at a high temperature to prevent the cotton threads from breaking, and the air was thick with dust that settled in the lungs and stayed there. Children as young as eight worked alongside adults, crawling beneath the machines to sweep away waste cotton. The noise was such that workers communicated by lip-reading, and many were partially deaf by the age of thirty. A working day lasted fourteen hours, with thirty minutes allowed for dinner. By evening, the workers emerged pale and stooped, blinking in whatever light remained."',
    modelAnswer:
      'The writer presents several key points about the harsh conditions of Victorian factory life.\n\nFirstly, workers faced strict timekeeping rules. They were summoned by a bell at 5:30 a.m. and penalised severely for lateness — arriving even minutes after six o\'clock meant losing an entire day\'s pay. This suggests that factory owners prioritised discipline and control over fairness.\n\nSecondly, the physical environment was dangerous to health. The rooms were kept artificially hot to protect the cotton during production, and the atmosphere was polluted with fibre dust that caused long-term respiratory damage. Workers had no protection from these hazards.\n\nThirdly, child labour was commonplace. Children from the age of eight were employed to perform dangerous tasks such as cleaning underneath moving machinery. They were not given lighter or safer duties but were expected to work in the same conditions as adults.\n\nFourthly, the noise levels were damaging. The machinery was so loud that verbal communication was impossible, forcing workers to read lips. Prolonged exposure resulted in significant hearing loss, with many workers becoming partially deaf before middle age.\n\nFifthly, the working hours were extreme. A standard shift lasted fourteen hours with only a half-hour break for a meal. This left workers with almost no time for rest, family, or any activity outside the factory.\n\nFinally, the cumulative physical toll is captured in the writer\'s description of workers leaving the factory in a visibly deteriorated state — pale, hunched, and disoriented by natural light. This image powerfully conveys how factory work eroded both health and dignity.\n\nIn summary, the writer depicts factory life as exploitative, physically destructive, and dehumanising, with workers — including very young children — subjected to conditions that damaged their bodies and shortened their lives.',
